04413nam a22005295i 9780822392200DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223922007 a10.1515/97808223922002doi  a(DE-B1597)553661  a(OCoLC)1181643196  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF1210 -- M75 2009 7aHIS0250002bisacsh04a305.868/721 aMraz, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLooking for Mexico :bModern Visual Culture and National Identity /cJohn Mraz. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b53 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAuthor's Note -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne War, Portraits, Mexican Types, and Porfirian Progress (1847-1910) -- tTwo Revolution and Culture (1910-1940) -- tThree Cinema and Celebrities in the Golden Age -- tFour Illustrated Magazines, Photojournalism, and Historia gráfica (1940-1968) -- tFive New Ocular Cultures and the Old Battle to Visualize the Past and Present (1968-2007) -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Looking for Mexico, a leading historian of visual culture, John Mraz, provides a panoramic view of Mexico's modern visual culture from the U.S. invasion of 1847 to the present. Along the way, he illuminates the powerful role of photographs, films, illustrated magazines, and image-filled history books in the construction of national identity, showing how Mexicans have both made themselves and been made with the webs of significance spun by modern media. Central to Mraz's book is photography, which was distributed widely throughout Mexico in the form of cartes-de-visite, postcards, and illustrated magazines. Mraz analyzes the work of a broad range of photographers, including Guillermo Kahlo, Winfield Scott, Hugo Brehme, Agustín Víctor Casasola, Tina Modotti, Manuel Álvarez Bravo, Héctor García, Pedro Meyer, and the New Photojournalists. He also examines representations of Mexico's past in the country's influential picture histories: popular, large-format, multivolume series replete with thousands of photographs and an assortment of texts.Turning to film, Mraz compares portrayals of the Mexican Revolution by Fernando de Fuentes to the later movies of Emilio Fernández and Gabriel Figueroa. He considers major stars of Golden Age cinema as gender archetypes for mexicanidad, juxtaposing the charros (hacienda cowboys) embodied by Pedro Infante, Pedro Armendáriz, and Jorge Negrete with the effacing women: the mother, Indian, and shrew as played by Sara García, Dolores del Río, and María Félix. Mraz also analyzes the leading comedians of the Mexican screen, representations of the 1968 student revolt, and depictions of Frida Kahlo in films made by Paul Leduc and Julie Taymor. Filled with more than fifty illustrations, Looking for Mexico is an exuberant plunge into Mexico's national identity, its visual culture, and the connections between the two.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392200zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822392200423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822392200.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles